          "body": "Verses 8–14 reveal a judgment that is neither indiscriminate nor mechanical. Three groups receive three different outcomes. The main population and the defectors are exiled to Babylon (39:9) — the mass of Jerusalem's people swept up in the covenant curse of Deuteronomy 28:36. The poorest, who had nothing, are left in the land and given vineyards and fields (39:10) — an inversion of expected economics. The ones who had nothing now receive something; the ones who had everything lose it. Then Jeremiah, imprisoned by Judah's own king, is released by Nebuchadnezzar's personal command (39:11–14). The pagan emperor who has just ordered the burning of Jerusalem issues by name an order protecting the man who told Jerusalem to submit to him. The theological irony is radical: Babylon executes God's judgment on Jerusalem and simultaneously executes God's protection of His prophet. Nebuchadnezzar does not know he is fulfilling two contradictory-looking divine purposes in the same military campaign. Jeremiah ends up quietly at home among his people (39:14) — not exalted, not vindicated with a parade, simply free. God's protection is not always spectacular; sometimes it is just: he stayed."
