          "title": "The oracle to Ebed-melech — trust as the decisive variable",
          "body": "Verses 15–18 form the chapter's theological climax, though they are often treated as a footnote. The structure is deliberate: the oracle came to Jeremiah while he was still confined (39:15) — before his release, before the fall, in the dark of the court of the guardhouse. God's word of rescue preceded the rescue. Ebed-melech was a Cushite, a foreigner, an ethnic outsider to the Mosaic covenant, a man whose very name ('servant of the king') defined him by his service to another. Yet the oracle to him is the most personal, most intimate in the chapter: 'I will deliver you... you will not be given into the hand of the men you dread... I will certainly rescue you... because you have trusted in Me.' The four-fold promise rests on a single foundation: batach — trust. Ebed-melech had demonstrated that trust three months earlier when he appealed to the king and pulled Jeremiah out of the cistern with rope and rags (38:7–13). He risked royal displeasure to do an act of mercy for a prophet whose message was unpopular. That single act of trust is what God remembered and rewarded on the day everything else collapsed. Peter Davids' insight on James 2:22 — that faith is made complete by works — finds its Old Testament echo here: Ebed-melech's trust in God was not merely intellectual; it expressed itself in rope and rags for a dying man, and God counted it as the kind of trust that earns rescue."
